Wash and dry produce.

Halve, peel, and dice @yellow onion{1}(halved, peeled, and diced).

Thinly slice half the @jalapeño{1}(halved) into rounds; mince remaining
jalapeño. TIP: Remove ribs and seeds for less heat.

Heat a large drizzle of @cooking oil{2%teaspoon} in a medium #pot{} over
medium-high heat. Add onion and minced jalapeño; season with @salt{} and
@pepper{}. Cook, stirring, until softened, ~{5-7%minutes}.

Add @ground plant-based protein{9%ounce}, @Mexican spice blend{1%tablespoon},
@Southwest spice blend{1%tablespoon}, salt, and pepper to pot. Cook, breaking
up protein into pieces, until browned and cooked through, ~{4-6%minutes}.

Stir @tomato paste{1.5%ounce} into pot. Cook, stirring, until dark red and
combined, ~{1-2%minutes}.

Stir in @diced tomatoes{1%14oz can}, @black beans{1%13.4oz can} and their
liquid, @mushroom stock concentrate{1}, @water{1/4%cup}, salt, and pepper.
Bring to a simmer and cook, uncovered, until thickened, ~{8-10%minutes}.

Turn off heat. Taste and season with salt and pepper.

== Hot Sauce Crema ==

Meanwhile, in a #small bowl{}, combine @sour cream{2%tablespoon} with
@hot sauce{1%teaspoon} to taste; season with salt and pepper. Stir in water
1 tsp at a time until mixture reaches a drizzling consistency.

== To Serve ==

Divide chili between #bowls{}. Top with @Monterey Jack cheese{1/4%cup}(shredded),
hot sauce crema, and as much sliced jalapeño as you like.

> A good chili has well-seasoned protein, creamy beans, and tender vegetables.
> This vegetarian chili is made with plant-based protein and beans, and we're
> pretty sure you'll agree: it's one of the greats.
>
> These bowls are adorned with some delicious fixings: tangy hot sauce crema
> and melty Monterey Jack. If you've got some on hand, why not crumble up some
> tortilla chips and sprinkle them on top for a crunch?